title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(1)\implies (2):]]></fr:tex> Assume <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> is perfect. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in \mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk  / \mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> be the <fr:link
type="local"
href="nt-001S.xml"
addr="nt-001S"
title="Splitting Field of a Polynomial">splitting field</fr:link> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x^{s}-a]]></fr:tex> and let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta \in \Bbbk ]]></fr:tex> be such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta ^{p}=a]]></fr:tex>. Then the characteristic polynomial <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m_{\beta }(x)]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> is irreducible, and divides
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[x^{p}-a=x^{p}-\beta ^{p}=(x-\beta )^{p}.]]></fr:tex>
Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> is perfect, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m_{\beta }]]></fr:tex> has no repeated roots, so
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[m_{\beta }=x-\beta ,]]></fr:tex>
and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\beta \in \mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(2)\implies (3):]]></fr:tex> (<fr:link
type="local"
href="nst-002J.xml"
addr="nst-002J"
title="Proof by contradiction">Proof by contradiction</fr:link>.) Assume <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\phi ]]></fr:tex> is surjective. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk  / \mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> be a finite extension, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha \in \Bbbk ]]></fr:tex>, and let
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[m_{\alpha }(x)=a_{n}x^{n}+a_{n-1}x^{n-1}+…+a_{1}x+a_{0}.]]></fr:tex>
Assume for contradiction <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m_{\alpha }(x)]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link
type="local"
href="nt-0025.xml"
addr="nt-0025"
title="Separable Polynomial">inseparable</fr:link>, so that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m'_{\alpha }(x)=0]]></fr:tex> and <fr:link
type="local"
href="nt-0029.xml"
addr="nt-0029"
title="Inseparable polynomial over field with characteristic p has p divide the nonzero coefficients of its derivative">then we see</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p\mathrel {\bigm |} k]]></fr:tex> whenever <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{k}\neq 0]]></fr:tex>. Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\phi ]]></fr:tex> is surjective, each <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{k}=b_{k}^{p}]]></fr:tex> for some <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[b_{k}\in \mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>. Then
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[m_{\alpha }(x)=(b_{m}x^{m})^{p}+(b_{m-1}x^{m-1})^{p-1}+…+(b_{1}x)^{p}+b_{0}^{p}=(q(x))^{p},]]></fr:tex>
where
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[q(x)=b_{m}x^{m}+…+b_{1}x+b_{0},]]></fr:tex>
which contradicts the irreducibility of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m_{\alpha }(x)]]></fr:tex>. Hence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m_{\alpha }(x)]]></fr:tex> must be separable.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(3)\implies (1):]]></fr:tex> Suppose <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p(x)\in \mathbb {F}[x]]]></fr:tex> is irreducible. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Bbbk =\mathbb {F}[x]/(p(x))]]></fr:tex> is a separable extension of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>. If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha \in \Bbbk ]]></fr:tex> is the image of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in \mathbb {F}[x]]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m_{\alpha }(x)=p(x)]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link
type="local"
href="nt-0025.xml"
addr="nt-0025"
title="Separable Polynomial">separable</fr:link>.</fr:p><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 

 
   
